Dijkstra's algorithm is a widely used algorithm for finding the shortest path between nodes in a graph. It works by maintaining a priority queue of vertices, ordered by their distance from the source vertex. Starting from the source vertex, the algorithm repeatedly extracts the vertex with the smallest distance from the priority queue and expands to its neighbors.

Here's a sample implementation of Dijkstra's algorithm in C++:
```c
#include <iostream>
#include <queue>
#include <vector>
#include <utility>
#include <limits>

using namespace std;

typedef pair<int, int> pii;

const int INF = numeric_limits<int>::max();
const int MAXN = 1e5 + 5;

vector<vector<pii>> adj[MAXN];
int n;

int dijkstra(int start) {
    int dist[MAXN];
    memset(dist, INF, sizeof dist);
    priority_queue<pii, vector<pii>, greater<pii>> pq;
    pq.emplace(0, start);
    dist[start] = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (dist[i] == INF) {
            continue;
        }
        for (auto edge : adj[i]) {
            int to = edge.first;
            int weight = edge.second;
            if (dist[to] > dist[i] + weight) {
                dist[to] = dist[i] + weight;
                pq.emplace(dist[to], to);
            }
        }
    }
    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        if (dist[i] == INF) {
            continue;
        }
        cout << "Dist[" << i << "] = " << dist[i] << endl;
    }
    return dist[n - 1];
}

int main() {
    cin >> n;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int x;
        cin >> x;
        int y;
        cin >> y;
        adj[i].emplace_back(x, y);
        adj[y].emplace_back(y, x);
    }
    int d = dijkstra(0);
    cout << d << endl;
    return 0;
}
```
In this implementation, the graph is represented as an adjacency list, where each vertex is associated with a list of its neighbors and their weights. The `adj` array stores the adjacency list for all vertices, and `n` is the number of vertices in the graph.

The `dijkstra` function takes a start vertex as input and returns the shortest distance from the start vertex to every other vertex. It uses a priority queue to keep track of the vertices to be processed, and `dist` is a vector that stores the distance to each vertex from the start vertex. The function first initializes `dist` with infinite distances, and then adds the start vertex to the priority queue with a distance of 0. It then repeatedly extracts the vertex with the smallest distance from the priority queue and updates the distances to its neighbors if a shorter path is found. The function ends by printing out the distances to all vertices.

To reverse a linked list in-place, we need to swap the nodes one by one from the head to the tail of the list. We can start by traversing the list in reverse order using a temporary pointer that points to the next node of the head. Then, we can swap the values of the head and the temporary pointer and move the temporary pointer one node ahead. We repeat this process until the head and the tail meet.

Here is the C code that implements this algorithm:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
};

// Reverses a linked list in-place
void reverse(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node* temp, * prev;
    temp = head;
    prev = NULL;

    while (temp && temp->next) {
        prev = temp;
        temp = temp->next->next;
    }

    if (!temp || !temp->next)
        return;

    prev->next = NULL;

    while (temp != head) {
        prev = temp;
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    prev->next = head->next;

    if (head->next)
        head->next->prev = prev;

    head->next = NULL;
    head->prev = prev;
}

int main() {
    struct Node* head = NULL;
    struct Node* node1 = NULL, * node2 = NULL, * node3 = NULL, * node4 = NULL;
    node1 = malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    node1->data = 1;
    node1->next = node2;
    node2 = malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    node2->data = 2;
    node2->next = node3;
    node3 = malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    node3->data = 3;
    node3->next = node4;
    node4 = malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    node4->data = 4;
    node4->next = NULL;
    head = node1;
    reverse(head);
    printf("Linked list after reversing: ");
    struct Node* curr = head;
    while (curr) {
        printf("%d ", curr->data);
        curr = curr->next;
    }
    printf("null\n");
    return 0;
}
```

In this code, we define a struct Node to represent each node of the linked list. We then create a temporary pointer called prev that will be used to keep track of the previous node of the head. We also create a pointer called temp that will be used to traverse the list in reverse order.

We start by traversing the list in reverse order until we reach the end of the list (i.e., the node that has no next pointer). We then swap the values of the head and the last node (i.e., the node that has no next pointer) and set the next pointer of the last node to NULL.

We then traverse the list again, this time from the head to the end, and swap the values of the nodes one by one. We also set the prev pointer of each node to the previous node and the next pointer of the last node to the head of the list.

Finally, we print the reversed linked list using a loop to traverse the list from the head to the tail.

To implement a queue data structure using two stacks, we will use two stacks to store the elements of the queue. One stack will be used to store the elements in the order they are added to the queue, and the other stack will be used to remove elements from the queue in the opposite order.

Here is an implementation in Java:
```
import java.util.Stack;

public class QueueUsingStacks {
    private Stack<Integer> frontStack;
    private Stack<Integer> backStack;
    private int capacity;

    public QueueUsingStacks(int capacity) {
        this.capacity = capacity;
        this.frontStack = new Stack<>();
        this.backStack = new Stack<>();
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return frontStack.isEmpty() && backStack.isEmpty();
    }

    public int size() {
        return frontStack.size() + backStack.size();
    }

    public boolean isFull() {
        return size() == capacity;
    }

    public boolean enQueue(int element) {
        if (isFull()) {
            return false;
        }
        frontStack.push(element);
        return true;
    }

    public int deQueue() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            return -1;
        }
        backStack.push(frontStack.pop());
        return backStack.pop();
    }
}
```
