For each element in the first string and each element in the second string, we will compare them and find the length of the longest common subsequence that ends at that element. If the element in the first string is greater than the element in the second string, then we cannot include the element in the common subsequence, so we will set the length of the common subsequence to 0. Otherwise, we will continue searching for the longest common subsequence that ends at that element.

To find the longest common subsequence that ends at an element, we will search backwards from that element and find the longest common subsequence that ends at each previous element. We will continue searching backwards until we find the longest common subsequence that ends at the first element of the first string.

Once we have filled the matrix with the length of the longest common subsequence, we will find the maximum value in the matrix to get the length of the longest common subsequence.

Here is the Java code that implements the above approach:

```
public static String longestCommonSubsequence(String s1, String s2) {
    int m = s1.length();
    int n = s2.length();
    int[][] dp = new int[m + 1][n + 1];

    for (int i = 0; i <= m; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j <= n; j++) {
            if (i == 0 || j == 0) {
                dp[i][j] = 0;
            } else if (s1.charAt(i - 1) == s2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
                if (dp[i][j] > dp[i][j - 1]) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i][j - 1];
                }
            } else {
                dp[i][j] = 0;
            }
        }
    }

    return s1.substring(dpm[0][n], dpm[m][n]);
}

